# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: particle-aggregation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] In spectroscopy, **absorbance** (abbreviated as **A**) is a logarithmic value which describes the portion of a beam of light which does not pass through a sample.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Whilst the name refers to the absorption of light, other interactions of light with a sample (reflection, scattering) may also contribute to attenuation of the beam passing through the sample.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] The term "internal absorbance" is sometimes used to describe beam attenuation caused by absorption, while "attenuance" or "experimental absorbance" can be used to emphasize that beam attenuation can be caused by other phenomena.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] The roots of the term absorbance are in the Beer–Lambert law (or Beer's law).
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] As light moves through a medium, it will become dimmer as it is being "extinguished".
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Pierre Bouguer recognized that this extinction (now often called attenuation) was not linear with distance traveled through the medium, but related to what is now referred to as an exponential function.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] where $\mu$ is called an attenuation constant (a term used in various fields where a signal is transmitted though a medium) or coefficient.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] The amount of light transmitted decreases exponentially with distance.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] If the size of a detector is very small compared to the distance traveled by the light, any light that is scattered by a particle, either in the forward or backward direction, will not strike the detector.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] (Bouguer was studying astronomical phenomena, so this condition was met.) In such cases, a plot of $-\ln(T)$ as a function of wavelength will yield a superposition of the effects of absorption and scattering.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Because the absorption portion is more distinct and tends to ride on a background of the scatter portion, it is often used to identify and quantify the absorbing species.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Consequently, this is often referred to as absorption spectroscopy, and the plotted quantity is called "absorbance", symbolized as $\mathrm {A}$ .
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Some disciplines by convention use decadic (base 10) absorbance rather than Napierian (natural) absorbance, resulting in $\mathrm {A} _{10}=\mu _{10}d$ (with the subscript 10 usually not shown).
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Within a homogeneous medium such as a solution, there is no scattering.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] In this case, researched extensively by August Beer, the concentration of the absorbing species follows the same linear contribution to absorbance as the path-length.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Additionally, the contributions of individual absorbing species are additive.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] This is a very favorable situation, and made absorbance an absorption metric far preferable to absorption fraction (absorptance).
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] This is the case for which the term "absorbance" was first used.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] For samples which scatter light, absorbance is defined as "the negative logarithm of one minus absorptance (absorption fraction: $\alpha$ ) as measured on a uniform sample".
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] For decadic absorbance, this may be symbolized as $\mathrm {A} _{10}=-\log _{10}(1-\alpha )$ .
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] If a sample both transmits and remits light, and is not luminescent, the fraction of light absorbed ( $\alpha$ ), remitted ( R ), and transmitted ( T ) add to 1: $\alpha +R+T=1$ .
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] For a sample which does not scatter, $R=0$ , and $1-\alpha =T$ , yielding the formula for absorbance of a material discussed below.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Even though this absorbance function is very useful with scattering samples, the function does not have the same desirable characteristics as it does for non-scattering samples.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] There is, however, a property called absorbing power which may be estimated for these samples.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] The absorbing power of a single unit thickness of material making up a scattering sample is the same as the absorbance of the same thickness of the material in the absence of scatter.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Absorbance is dimensionless, and in particular is not a length, though it is a monotonically increasing function of path length, and approaches zero as the path length approaches zero.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Although absorbance is properly unitless, it is sometimes reported in "absorbance units", or AU.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Many people, including scientific researchers, wrongly state the results from absorbance measurement experiments in terms of these made-up units.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Absorbance is a number that measures the *attenuation* of the transmitted radiant power in a material.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Attenuation can be caused by the physical process of "absorption", but also reflection, scattering, and other physical processes.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Absorbance of a material is approximately equal to its attenuance when both the absorbance is much less than 1 and the emittance of that material (not to be confused with radiant exitance or emissivity) is much less than the absorbance.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] The use of the term "molar absorptivity" for molar attenuation coefficient is discouraged.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Absorbance is a widely used measurement in quantitative absorption spectroscopy.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] For quantitative purposes, absorbance is often measured on a sample solution held in a cuvette, where the solution is sufficiently dilute that the linear relationship of the Beer's law holds.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] The cuvette provides a known and consistent path length for the light beam passing through the sample.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Measuring first the absorbance of the cuvette and a "blank" solution containing no analyte, differences in absorbance between samples can be used to quantity the analyte.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] Spectrometers generally measure absorbance separately for a range of wavelengths: this data is then plotted as absorbance vs. wavelength.
[src:particle-aggregation/absorbance] For example, if the filter has 0.1% transmittance (0.001 transmittance, which is 3 absorbance units), its shade number would be 8.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] An **aerosol** is a suspension of fine solid particles or liquid droplets in air or another gas.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Aerosols can be generated from natural or human causes.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The scientific term *aerosol* refers to the mixture of particulates in gas, and not to the particulate matter alone.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The liquid or solid particles in an aerosol have diameters typically less than 1 μm.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Larger particles with a significant settling speed make the mixture a suspension, although the distinction is not clear.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Examples of natural aerosols are fog, mist, and dust from geological or biological sources.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Certain infections spread by means of small droplets in the breath, sometimes called bioaerosols.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Volcanic aerosol forms in the stratosphere after an eruption as droplets of sulfuric acid that can prevail for up to two years, and reflect sunlight, lowering temperature.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Desert dust, mineral particles blown to high altitudes, absorb heat and may be responsible for inhibiting storm cloud formation.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] In everyday language, *aerosol* often refers to a dispensing system that delivers a consumer product from a spray can.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Other examples of human caused aerosols include perfume from atomizers, medical treatments for respiratory illnesses, dust from material or industrial sources, smoke, irrigation mist, sprayed pesticides, particulate air pollutants, and mist from the discharge at hydroelectric dams.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Human-made sulfate aerosols, primarily from burning oil and coal, affect the behavior of clouds.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] When aerosols absorb pollutants, it facilitates the deposition of pollutants to the surface of the earth as well as to bodies of water.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This has the potential to be damaging to both the environment and human health.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Ship tracks are clouds that form around the exhaust released by ships into the still ocean air.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Water molecules collect around the tiny particles (aerosols) from exhaust to form a cloud seed.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] More and more water accumulates on the seed until a visible cloud is formed.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] In the case of ship tracks, the cloud seeds are stretched over a long narrow path where the wind has blown the ship's exhaust, so the resulting clouds resemble long strings over the ocean.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The warming caused by human-produced greenhouse gases has been somewhat offset by the cooling effect of human-produced aerosols.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] In 2020, regulations on fuel significantly cut sulfur dioxide emissions from international shipping by approximately 80%, leading to an unexpected global geoengineering termination shock.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Aerosol is defined as a suspension system of solid or liquid particles in a gas.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] An aerosol includes both the particles and the suspending gas, which is usually air.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Meteorologists and climatologists often refer to them as particle matter, while the classification in sizes ranges like PM2.5 or PM10, is useful in the field of atmospheric pollution as these size range play a role in ascertain the harmful effects in human health.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Donnan presumably first used the term *aerosol* during World War I to describe an aero-solution, clouds of microscopic particles in air.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This term developed analogously to the term hydrosol, a colloid system with water as the dispersed medium.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] *Primary aerosols* contain particles introduced directly into the gas; *secondary aerosols* form through gas-to-particle conversion.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Key aerosol groups include sulfates, organic carbon, black carbon, nitrates, mineral dust, and sea salt, they usually clump together to form a complex mixture.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Various types of aerosol, classified according to physical form and how they were generated, include dust, fume, mist, smoke and fog.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] There are several measures of aerosol concentration.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Environmental science and environmental health often use the *mass concentration* (*M*), defined as the mass of particulate matter per unit volume, in units such as μg/m3.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Also commonly used is the *number concentration* (*N*), the number of particles per unit volume, in units such as number per m3 or number per cm3.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Particle size has a major influence on particle properties, and the aerosol particle radius or diameter (*dp*) is a key property used to characterise aerosols.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] A *monodisperse* aerosol, producible in the laboratory, contains particles of uniform size.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Most aerosols, however, as *polydisperse* colloidal systems, exhibit a range of particle sizes.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Liquid droplets are almost always nearly spherical, but scientists use an *equivalent diameter* to characterize the properties of various shapes of solid particles, some very irregular.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The equivalent diameter is the diameter of a spherical particle with the same value of some physical property as the irregular particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The *equivalent volume diameter* (*de*) is defined as the diameter of a sphere of the same volume as that of the irregular particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Also commonly used is the aerodynamic diameter, *da*.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Several types of atmospheric aerosol have a significant effect on Earth's climate: volcanic, desert dust, sea-salt, that originating from biogenic sources and human-made.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Although all hydrometeors, solid and liquid, can be described as aerosols, a distinction is commonly made between such dispersions (i.e. clouds and precipitation) containing relatively large water drops or ice crystals, and aerosol particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The presence of aerosols in the Earth's atmosphere can influence its climate, as well as human health.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Volcanic eruptions release large amounts of sulphuric acid, hydrogen sulfide and hydrochloric acid into the atmosphere.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] These gases represent aerosols and eventually return to earth as acid rain, having a number of adverse effects on the environment and human life.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Aerosols interact with the Earth's energy budget in two ways, directly and indirectly.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Aerosol particles with an effective diameter smaller than 10 μm can enter the bronchi, while the ones with an effective diameter smaller than 2.5 μm can enter as far as the gas exchange region in the lungs, which can be hazardous to human health.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] For a monodisperse aerosol, a single number—the particle diameter—suffices to describe the size of the particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] However, more complicated particle-size distributions describe the sizes of the particles in a polydisperse aerosol.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This distribution defines the relative amounts of particles, sorted according to size.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] One approach to defining the particle size distribution uses a list of the sizes of every particle in a sample.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] However, this approach proves tedious to ascertain in aerosols with millions of particles and awkward to use.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Another approach splits the size range into intervals and finds the number (or proportion) of particles in each interval.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The particle size distribution can be approximated.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The normal distribution usually does not suitably describe particle size distributions in aerosols because of the skewness associated with a long tail of larger particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Also for a quantity that varies over a large range, as many aerosol sizes do, the width of the distribution implies negative particles sizes, which is not physically realistic.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] However, the normal distribution can be suitable for some aerosols, such as test aerosols, certain pollen grains and spores.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The log-normal distribution has no negative values, can cover a wide range of values, and fits many observed size distributions reasonably well.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] For low values of the Reynolds number (<1), true for most aerosol motion, Stokes' law describes the force of resistance on a solid spherical particle in a fluid.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] However, Stokes' law is only valid when the velocity of the gas at the surface of the particle is zero.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] For small particles (< 1 μm) that characterize aerosols, however, this assumption fails.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] To account for this failure, one can introduce the Cunningham correction factor, always greater than 1.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This allows us to calculate the terminal velocity of a particle undergoing gravitational settling in still air.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] is the terminal settling velocity of the particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The terminal velocity can also be derived for other kinds of forces.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] If Stokes' law holds, then the resistance to motion is directly proportional to speed.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] To account for the effect of the shape of non-spherical particles, a correction factor known as the *dynamic shape factor* is applied to Stokes' law.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The aerodynamic diameter of an irregular particle is defined as the diameter of the spherical particle with a density of 1000 kg/m3 and the same settling velocity as the irregular particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] One can apply the aerodynamic diameter to particulate pollutants or to inhaled drugs to predict where in the respiratory tract such particles deposit.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Pharmaceutical companies typically use aerodynamic diameter, not geometric diameter, to characterize particles in inhalable drugs.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The previous discussion focused on single aerosol particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] In contrast, *aerosol dynamics* explains the evolution of complete aerosol populations.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The concentrations of particles will change over time as a result of many processes.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] External processes that move particles outside a volume of gas under study include diffusion, gravitational settling, and electric charges and other external forces that cause particle migration.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] A second set of processes internal to a given volume of gas include particle formation (nucleation), evaporation, chemical reaction, and coagulation.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] A differential equation called the *Aerosol General Dynamic Equation* (GDE) characterizes the evolution of the number density of particles in an aerosol due to these processes.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] As particles and droplets in an aerosol collide with one another, they may undergo coalescence or aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This process leads to a change in the aerosol particle-size distribution, with the mode increasing in diameter as total number of particles decreases.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] On occasion, particles may shatter apart into numerous smaller particles; however, this process usually occurs primarily in particles too large for consideration as aerosols.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] where $\lambda$ is the mean free path of the suspending gas and d is the diameter of the particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] For particles in the *free molecular regime*, *Kn* >> 1; particles small compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] In this regime, particles interact with the suspending gas through a series of "ballistic" collisions with gas molecules.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] As such, they behave similarly to gas molecules, tending to follow streamlines and diffusing rapidly through Brownian motion.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] where *a* is the particle radius, *P*∞ and *PA* are the pressures far from the droplet and at the surface of the droplet respectively, *kb* is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *CA* is mean thermal velocity and *α* is mass accommodation coefficient.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The derivation of this equation assumes constant pressure and constant diffusion coefficient.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Particles are in the *continuum regime* when Kn << 1.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] In this regime, the particles are big compared to the mean free path of the suspending gas, meaning that the suspending gas acts as a continuous fluid flowing round the particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The *transition regime* contains all the particles in between the free molecular and continuum regimes or *Kn* ≈ 1.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The forces experienced by a particle are a complex combination of interactions with individual gas molecules and macroscopic interactions.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] where *I*cont is the mass flux in the continuum regime.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This formula is called the Fuchs-Sutugin interpolation formula.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] These equations do not take into account the heat release effect.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Aerosol partitioning theory governs condensation on and evaporation from an aerosol surface, respectively.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Condensation of mass causes the mode of the particle-size distributions of the aerosol to increase; conversely, evaporation causes the mode to decrease.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Nucleation is the process of forming aerosol mass from the condensation of a gaseous precursor, specifically a vapor.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Net condensation of the vapor requires supersaturation, a partial pressure greater than its vapor pressure.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Chemical reactions may increase the partial pressure of a gas or lower its vapor pressure.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The addition of additional vapor to the system may lower the equilibrium vapor pressure according to Raoult's law.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] There are two types of nucleation processes.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Gases preferentially condense onto surfaces of pre-existing aerosol particles, known as **heterogeneous nucleation**.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This process causes the diameter at the mode of particle-size distribution to increase with constant number concentration.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] With sufficiently high supersaturation and no suitable surfaces, particles may condense in the absence of a pre-existing surface, known as **homogeneous nucleation**.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This results in the addition of very small, rapidly growing particles to the particle-size distribution.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Water coats particles in aerosols, making them *activated*, usually in the context of forming a cloud droplet (such as natural cloud seeding by aerosols from trees in a forest).
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Following the Kelvin equation (based on the curvature of liquid droplets), smaller particles need a higher ambient relative humidity to maintain equilibrium than larger particles do.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] where $p_{s}$ is the saturation vapor pressure above a particle at equilibrium (around a curved liquid droplet), *p*0 is the saturation vapor pressure (flat surface of the same liquid) and *S* is the saturation ratio.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] where *rp* droplet radius, *σ* surface tension of droplet, *ρ* density of liquid, *M* molar mass, *T* temperature, and *R* molar gas constant.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Aerosols can either be measured in-situ or with remote sensing techniques either ground-based on airborne-based.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Particles can deposit in the nose, mouth, pharynx and larynx (the head airways region), deeper within the respiratory tract (from the trachea to the terminal bronchioles), or in the alveolar region.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The location of deposition of aerosol particles within the respiratory system strongly determines the health effects of exposure to such aerosols.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] This phenomenon led people to invent aerosol samplers that select a subset of the aerosol particles that reach certain parts of the respiratory system.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Examples of these subsets of the particle-size distribution of an aerosol, important in occupational health, include the inhalable, thoracic, and respirable fractions.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The fraction that can enter each part of the respiratory system depends on the deposition of particles in the upper parts of the airway.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The inhalable fraction of particles, defined as the proportion of particles originally in the air that can enter the nose or mouth, depends on external wind speed and direction and on the particle-size distribution by aerodynamic diameter.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The thoracic fraction is the proportion of the particles in ambient aerosol that can reach the thorax or chest region.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The respirable fraction is the proportion of particles in the air that can reach the alveolar region.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] To measure the respirable fraction of particles in air, a pre-collector is used with a sampling filter.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The pre-collector excludes particles as the airways remove particles from inhaled air.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The sampling filter collects the particles for measurement.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] It is common to use cyclonic separation for the pre-collector, but other techniques include impactors, horizontal elutriators, and large pore membrane filters.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] Two alternative size-selective criteria, often used in atmospheric monitoring, are PM10 and PM2.5.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] PM10 is defined by ISO as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 10 μm aerodynamic diameter* and PM2.5 as *particles which pass through a size-selective inlet with a 50% efficiency cut-off at 2.5 μm aerodynamic diameter*.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] PM10 corresponds to the "thoracic convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, Clause 6; PM2.5 corresponds to the "high-risk respirable convention" as defined in ISO 7708:1995, 7.1.
[src:particle-aggregation/aerosol] The United States Environmental Protection Agency replaced the older standards for particulate matter based on Total Suspended Particulate with another standard based on PM10 in 1987 and then introduced standards for PM2.5 (also known as fine particulate matter) in 1997.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] In physics, **backscatter** (or **backscattering**) is the reflection of waves, particles, or signals back to the direction from which they came.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] It is usually a diffuse reflection due to scattering, as opposed to specular reflection as from a mirror, although specular backscattering can occur at normal incidence with a surface.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Backscattering has important applications in astronomy, photography, and medical ultrasonography.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] The opposite effect is forward scatter, e.g. when a translucent material like a cloud diffuses sunlight, giving soft light.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Sometimes, the scattering is more or less isotropic, i.e. the incoming particles are scattered randomly in various directions, with no particular preference for backward scattering.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] In other cases, the scattering intensity is enhanced in backward direction.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Backscattering properties of a target are wavelength dependent and can also be polarization dependent.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Sensor systems using multiple wavelengths or polarizations can thus be used to infer additional information about target properties.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Backscattering is the principle behind radar systems.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] In weather radar, backscattering is proportional to the 6th power of the diameter of the target multiplied by its inherent reflective properties, provided the wavelength is larger than the particle diameter (Rayleigh scattering).
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Water is almost 4 times more reflective than ice but droplets are much smaller than snow flakes or hail stones.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] So the backscattering is dependent on a mix of these two factors.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] The strongest backscatter comes from hail and large graupel (solid ice) due to their sizes, but non-Rayleigh (Mie scattering) effects can confuse interpretation.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Another strong return is from melting snow or wet sleet, as they combine size and water reflectivity.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] They often show up as much higher rates of precipitation than actually occurring in what is called a *brightband.* Rain is a moderate backscatter, being stronger with large drops (such as from a thunderstorm) and much weaker with small droplets (such as mist or drizzle).
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Dual polarization weather radars measure backscatter at horizontal and vertical polarizations to infer shape information from the ratio of the vertical and horizontal signals.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] The backscattering method is also employed in fiber optics applications to detect optical faults.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Light propagating through a fiber-optic cable gradually attenuates due to Rayleigh scattering.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Faults are thus detected by monitoring the variation of part of the Rayleigh backscattered light.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Since the backscattered light attenuates exponentially as it travels along the optical fiber cable, the attenuation characteristic is represented in a logarithmic scale graph.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] If the slope of the graph is steep, then power loss is high.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] If the slope is gentle, then optical fiber has a satisfactory loss characteristic.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] The loss measurement by the backscattering method allows measurement of a fiber-optic cable at one end without cutting the optical fiber hence it can be conveniently used for the construction and maintenance of optical fibers.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] The term backscatter in photography refers to light from flash, strobe, or video lights reflecting back from particles in the lens's field of view, causing specks of light to appear in the photo.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] This gives rise to what are sometimes referred to as *orb artifacts*.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Photographic backscatter can result from snowflakes, rain or mist, or airborne dust.
[src:particle-aggregation/backscatter] Hence, the orb artifact is commonplace with small digital or film camera photographs.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Over a thousand types of cheese exist, produced in various countries.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Their styles, textures and flavors depend on the origin of the milk (including the animal's diet), whether they have been pasteurised, the butterfat content, the bacteria and mold, the processing, and how long they have been aged.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Herbs, spices, or wood smoke may be used as flavoring agents.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Other added ingredients may include black pepper, garlic, chives or cranberries.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A cheesemonger, or specialist seller of cheeses, may have expertise with selecting, purchasing, receiving, storing and ripening cheeses.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Most cheeses are acidified by bacteria, which turn milk sugars into lactic acid; the addition of rennet completes the curdling.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Vegetarian varieties of rennet are available; most are produced through fermentation by the fungus *Mucor miehei*, but others have been extracted from *Cynara* thistles.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] For a few cheeses, the milk is curdled by adding acids such as vinegar or lemon juice.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheese is valued for its portability, long shelf life, and high content of fat, protein, calcium, and phosphorus.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheese is more compact and has a longer shelf life than milk.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Hard cheeses, such as Cheddar and Parmesan, last longer than soft cheeses, such as Brie or goat's milk cheese.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The long storage life of some cheeses, especially when encased in a protective rind, allows producers to sell when markets are favourable.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Vacuum packaging of block-shaped cheeses and gas-flushing of plastic bags with mixtures of carbon dioxide and nitrogen are used for storage and mass distribution of cheeses in the 21st century, compared with the paper and twine that was used in the 20th and 19th century.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The word *cheese* comes from Latin **caseus**, from which the modern word casein is derived.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The earliest source is the conjectured proto-Indo-European root **kwat-*, which means "to ferment, become sour".
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] That gave rise to **cīese** or **cēse** (in Old English) and **chese** (in Middle English).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The origins of cheese predate recorded history.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] There is no conclusive evidence indicating where cheesemaking originated, whether in Europe, Central Asia or the Middle East.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The earliest proposed dates for the origin of cheesemaking range from around 8000 BCE, when sheep were first domesticated.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] There is a legend—with variations—about the discovery of cheese by an Arab trader who used this method of storing milk.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The earliest evidence of cheesemaking in the archaeological record dates back to 5500 BCE and is found in what is now Kuyavia, Poland, where strainers coated with milk-fat molecules have been found.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The earliest evidence of cheesemaking in the Mediterranean dates back to 5200 BCE, on the coast of the Dalmatia region of Croatia.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheesemaking may have begun independently of this by the pressing and salting of curdled milk to preserve it.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Observation that the effect of making cheese in an animal stomach gave more solid and better-textured curds may have led to the deliberate addition of rennet.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Early archeological evidence of Egyptian cheese has been found in Egyptian tomb murals, dating to about 2000 BCE.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A 2018 scientific paper stated that cheese dating to approximately 1200 BCE was found in ancient Egyptian tombs.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The earliest ever discovered preserved cheese was found on mummies in Xiaohe Cemetery in the Taklamakan Desert in Xinjiang, China, dating back as early as 1615 BCE.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Ancient Greek mythology credited Aristaeus with the discovery of cheese.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] 65 CE) details a cheesemaking process involving rennet coagulation, pressing of the curd, salting, and aging.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] According to Pliny the Elder, it had become a sophisticated enterprise by the time the Roman Empire came into being.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Pliny the Elder mentions in his writings *Caseus Helveticus*, a hard cheese produced by the Helvetii.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheese was an everyday food and cheesemaking a mature art in the Roman empire.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Pliny's *Natural History* (77 CE) devotes a chapter (XI, 97) to describing the diversity of cheeses enjoyed by Romans of the early Empire.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] He stated that the best cheeses came from the villages near Nîmes, but did not keep long and had to be eaten fresh.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheeses of the Alps and Apennines were as remarkable for their variety then as now.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A Ligurian cheese was noted for being made mostly from sheep's milk, and some cheeses produced nearby were stated to weigh as much as a thousand pounds each.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Goats' milk cheese was a recent taste in Rome, improved over the "medicinal taste" of Gaul's similar cheeses by smoking.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Of cheeses from overseas, Pliny preferred those of Bithynia in Asia Minor.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] 1000, Anglo-Saxons in England named a village by the River Thames *Ceswican*, meaning "Cheese farm".
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In 1022, it is mentioned that Vlach (Aromanian) shepherds from Thessaly and the Pindus mountains, in modern Greece, provided cheese for Constantinople.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Many cheeses popular today were first recorded in the late Middle Ages or after.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheeses such as Cheddar around 1500, Parmesan in 1597, Gouda in 1697, and Camembert in 1791 show post-Middle Ages dates.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In 1546, *The Proverbs of John Heywood* claimed "the moon is made of a green cheese" (*Greene* may refer here not to the color, as many now think, but to being new or unaged).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Variations on this sentiment were long repeated and NASA exploited this myth for an April Fools' Day spoof announcement in 2006.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] But with the spread, first of European imperialism, and later of Euro-American culture and food, cheese has gradually become known and increasingly popular worldwide.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The first factory for the industrial production of cheese opened in Switzerland in 1815, but large-scale production first found real success in the United States.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Credit usually goes to Jesse Williams, a dairy farmer from Rome, New York, who in 1851 started making cheese in an assembly-line fashion using the milk from neighboring farms; this made cheddar-like cheese one of the first US industrial foods.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Within decades, hundreds of such commercial dairy associations existed.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The 1860s saw the beginnings of mass-produced rennet, and by the turn of the century scientists were producing pure microbial cultures.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Before then, bacteria in cheesemaking had come from the environment or from recycling an earlier batch's whey; the pure cultures meant a more standardized cheese could be produced.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Factory-made cheese overtook traditional cheesemaking in the World War II era, and factories have been the source of most cheese in America and Europe ever since.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] By 2012, cheese was one of the most shoplifted items from supermarkets worldwide.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In 2022, world production of cheese from whole cow milk was 22.6 million tonnes, with the United States accounting for 28% of the total, followed by Germany, France, Italy and the Netherlands as secondary producers (table).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] As of 2021, the carbon footprint of a kilogram of cheese ranged from 6 to 12 kg of CO2eq, depending on the amount of milk used; accordingly, it is generally lower than beef or lamb, but higher than other foods.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] France, Iceland, Finland, Denmark and Germany were the highest consumers of cheese in 2014, averaging 25 kg (55 lb) per person per annum.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A required step in cheesemaking is to separate the milk into solid curds and liquid whey.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Usually this is done by acidifying (souring) the milk and adding rennet.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The acidification can be accomplished directly by the addition of an acid, such as vinegar, in a few cases (paneer, queso fresco).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] More commonly starter bacteria are employed instead which convert milk sugars into lactic acid.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The same bacteria (and the enzymes they produce) play a large role in the eventual flavor of aged cheeses.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Most cheeses are made with starter bacteria from the *Lactococcus*, *Lactobacillus*, or *Streptococcus* genera.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Swiss starter cultures include *Propionibacterium freudenreichii*, which produces propionic acid and carbon dioxide gas bubbles during aging, giving Emmental cheese its holes or eyes.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Some fresh cheeses are curdled only by acidity, but most cheeses have added rennet, which sets the cheese into a strong and rubbery gel compared to the fragile curds produced by acidic coagulation alone.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] It allows curdling at a lower acidity—important because flavor-making bacteria are inhibited in high-acidity environments.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In general, softer, smaller, fresher cheeses are curdled with a greater proportion of acid to rennet than harder, larger, longer-aged varieties.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] While rennet was traditionally produced via extraction from the inner mucosa of the fourth stomach chamber of slaughtered young, unweaned calves, most rennet used today in cheesemaking is produced recombinantly.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The majority of the applied chymosin is retained in the whey and, at most, may be present in cheese in trace quantities.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In ripe cheese, the type and provenance of chymosin used in production cannot be determined.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] At this point, the cheese has set into a very moist gel.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Some soft cheeses are now essentially complete: they are drained, salted, and packaged.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] For most of the rest, the curd is cut into small cubes.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] This allows water to drain from the individual pieces of curd.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Some hard cheeses are then heated to temperatures in the range of 35–55 °C (95–131 °F).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] This forces more whey from the cut curd, and changes the taste of the finished cheese, affecting both the bacterial culture and the milk chemistry.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheeses that are heated to the higher temperatures are usually made with thermophilic starter bacteria that survive this step—either *Lactobacilli* or *Streptococci*.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Salt has roles in cheese besides adding a salty flavor.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] It preserves cheese from spoiling, draws moisture from the curd, and firms cheese's texture in an interaction with its proteins.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Some cheeses are salted from the outside with dry salt or brine washes.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Most cheeses have the salt mixed directly into the curds.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Most cheeses are given their final shape by pressing the curds into a mold or form: the more pressure is applied, the harder the cheese.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The pressure drives out moisture—the molds are designed to allow water to escape—and unifies the curds into a single solid body.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A newborn cheese is usually salty yet bland in flavor and, for harder varieties, rubbery in texture.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] These qualities are sometimes enjoyed—cheese curds are eaten on their own—but normally cheeses are left to rest under controlled conditions.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] This aging period (called ripening, or, from the French, *affinage*) lasts from a few days to several years.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] As a cheese ages, microbes and enzymes transform texture and intensify flavor.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] This transformation is largely a result of the breakdown of casein proteins and milkfat into a complex mix of amino acids, amines, and fatty acids.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Some cheeses have additional bacteria or molds intentionally introduced before or during aging.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In traditional cheesemaking, these microbes might be already present in the aging room; they are allowed to settle and grow on the stored cheeses.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] More often today, prepared cultures are used, giving more consistent results and putting fewer constraints on the environment where the cheese ages.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] These cheeses include soft ripened cheeses such as Brie and Camembert; blue cheeses such as Roquefort, Stilton, Gorgonzola; and rind-washed cheeses such as Limburger.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] There are many types of cheese, with around 500 different varieties recognized by the International Dairy Federation, more than 400 identified by Walter and Hargrove, more than 500 by Burkhalter, and more than 1,000 by Sandine and Elliker.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The method most commonly and traditionally used is based on moisture content, which is then further discriminated by fat content and curing or ripening methods.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The British Cheese Board once claimed that Britain had about 700 distinct local cheeses.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] France and Italy have perhaps 400 each; a French proverb says there is a different French cheese for every day of the year; and Charles de Gaulle once asked "how can you govern a country in which there are 246 kinds of cheese?".
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] At refrigerator temperatures, the fat in a piece of cheese is as hard as unsoftened butter, and its protein structure is stiff as well.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Flavor and odor compounds are less easily liberated when cold.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] For improvements in flavor and texture, it is widely advised that cheeses warm up to room temperature before eating.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] If the cheese is further warmed, to 26–32 °C (79–90 °F), the fats begin to "sweat out" as they go beyond soft to fully liquid.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Above room temperatures, most hard cheeses melt.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Rennet-curdled cheeses have a gel-like protein matrix that is broken down by heat.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] When enough protein bonds are broken, the cheese itself turns from a solid to a viscous liquid.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Soft, high-moisture cheeses melt at around 55 °C (131 °F), while hard, low-moisture cheeses such as Parmesan remain solid until they reach about 82 °C (180 °F).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Acid-set cheeses, including halloumi, paneer, some whey cheeses and many varieties of fresh goat cheese, have a protein structure that remains intact at high temperatures.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] When cooked, these cheeses just get firmer as water evaporates.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Some cheeses, like raclette, melt smoothly; many tend to become stringy or suffer from a separation of their fats.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Many of these can be coaxed into melting smoothly in the presence of acids or starch.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Fondue, with wine providing the acidity, is a good example of a smoothly melted cheese dish.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Elastic stringiness is a quality that is sometimes enjoyed, in dishes including pizza and Welsh rarebit.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Even a melted cheese eventually turns solid again, after enough moisture is cooked off.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The saying "you can't melt cheese twice" (meaning "some things can only be done once") refers to the fact that oils leach out during the first melting and are gone, leaving the non-meltable solids behind.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] As its temperature continues to rise, cheese browns and eventually burns.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Browned, partially burned cheese has a distinct flavor of its own and is frequently used in cooking (e.g., sprinkling atop items before baking them).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A **cheeseboard** (or cheese course) may be served at the end of a meal before or following dessert, or replacing the last course.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The British tradition is to have cheese after dessert, accompanied by sweet wines like port.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In France, cheese is consumed before dessert, with robust red wine.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A cheeseboard typically has contrasting cheeses with accompaniments, such as crackers, biscuits, grapes, nuts, celery or chutney.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Sainte-Maure de Touraine, Pantysgawn, Crottin de Chavignol).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A cheeseboard 70 feet (21 m) long was used to feature the variety of cheeses manufactured in Wisconsin, where the state legislature recognizes a "cheesehead" hat as a state symbol.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The nutritional value of cheese varies widely.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Low-fat cottage cheese is 2% fat and 11% protein while dry queso seco cheese is 24% fat and 25% protein, and full-fat cream cheese is 34% fat and 6% protein.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In general, cheese is a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of calcium, protein, phosphorus, sodium and saturated fat.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A 17-gram (one slice) serving of cheddar cheese contains about 4 grams (0.14 oz) of protein and 120 milligrams of calcium.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A number of food safety agencies around the world have warned of the risks of raw-milk cheeses.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Food and Drug Administration states that soft raw-milk cheeses can cause "serious infectious diseases including listeriosis, brucellosis, salmonellosis and tuberculosis".
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] It is U.S. law since 1944 that all raw-milk cheeses (including imports since 1951) must be aged at least 60 days.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Australia has a wide ban on raw-milk cheeses as well, though in recent years exceptions have been made for Swiss Gruyère, Emmental and Sbrinz, and for French Roquefort.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] There is a trend for cheeses to be pasteurized even when not required by law.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Pregnant women may face an additional risk from cheese: the U.S.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Centers for Disease Control has warned pregnant women against eating soft-ripened cheeses and blue-veined cheeses, due to the listeria risk, which can cause miscarriage or harm the fetus.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Among the few cheeses in Southeast and East Asian cuisines is paneer, a fresh acid-set cheese.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In Nepal, the Dairy Development Corporation commercially manufactures cheese made from yak milk and a hard cheese made from either cow or yak milk known as chhurpi.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Bhutan produces a similar cheese called Datshi, which is a staple in most Bhutanese curries.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The national dish of Bhutan, ema datshi, is made from homemade yak or mare milk cheese and hot peppers.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] In Yunnan, China, several ethnic minority groups produce Rushan and Rubing from cow's milk.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Cheese consumption may be increasing in China, with annual sales doubling from 1996 to 2003 (to a still small 30 million U.S. dollars a year).
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Strict followers of the dietary laws of Islam and Judaism must avoid cheeses made with rennet from animals not slaughtered in accordance with halal or kosher laws respectively.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Rennet derived from animal slaughter, and thus cheese made with animal-derived rennet, is not vegetarian.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Most widely available vegetarian cheeses are made using rennet produced by fermentation of the fungus *Mucor miehei*.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Vegans and other dairy-avoiding people do not eat dairy cheese, but some vegan cheeses (soy or almond) are used as substitutes.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Even in cultures with long cheese traditions, consumers may perceive some cheeses that are especially pungent-smelling, or mold-bearing varieties such as Limburger, Stilton or Roquefort, as unpalatable.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Such cheeses are an acquired taste because they are processed using molds or microbiological cultures, allowing odor and flavor molecules to resemble those in rotten foods.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] There is some support from studies that dairy products can help with insomnia.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Scientists have debated how cheese might affect sleep.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] A folk belief that cheese eaten close to bedtime can cause nightmares may have arisen from the Charles Dickens novella *A Christmas Carol*, in which Ebenezer Scrooge attributes his visions of Jacob Marley to the cheese he ate.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] This belief can be found in folklore that predates this story.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] The theory has been disproven multiple times, although night cheese may cause vivid dreams or otherwise disrupt sleep due to its high saturated fat content, according to studies by the British Cheese Board.
[src:particle-aggregation/cheese] Other studies indicate it may actually make people dream less.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] Particles finer than 0.1 μm (10−7m) in water remain continuously in motion due to electrostatic charge (often negative) which causes them to repel each other.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] Once their electrostatic charge is neutralized by the use of a coagulant chemical, the finer particles start to collide and agglomerate (collect together) under the influence of Van der Waals forces.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] These larger and heavier particles are called flocs.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] Flocculants, or flocculating agents (also known as flocking agents), are chemicals that promote flocculation by causing colloids and other suspended particles in liquids to aggregate, forming a floc.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] Flocculants are used in water treatment processes to improve the sedimentation or filterability of small particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] For example, a flocculant may be used in swimming pool or drinking water filtration to aid removal of microscopic particles which would otherwise cause the water to be turbid (cloudy) and which would be difficult or impossible to remove by filtration alone.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] Many flocculants are multivalent cations such as aluminium, iron, calcium or magnesium.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] These positively charged molecules interact with negatively charged particles and molecules to reduce the barriers to aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] In addition, many of these chemicals, under appropriate pH and other conditions such as temperature and salinity, react with water to form insoluble hydroxides which, upon precipitating, link together to form long chains or meshes, physically trapping small particles into the larger floc.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] Long-chain polymer flocculants, such as modified polyacrylamides, are manufactured and sold by flocculant producers.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] These can be supplied in dry or liquid form for use in the flocculation process.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] The most common liquid polyacrylamide is supplied as an emulsion with 10-40% actives and the rest is a non-aqueous carrier fluid, surfactants and latex.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] This form allows easy handling of viscous polymers at high concentrations.
[src:particle-aggregation/clarifying-agent] These emulsion polymers require "activation" — inversion of the emulsion so that the polymer's molecules form an aqueous solution.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] In water treatment, **coagulation** and flocculation involve the addition of compounds that promote the clumping of fine floc into larger floc so that they can be more easily separated from the water.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulation is a chemical process that involves neutralization of charge whereas flocculation is a physical process and does not involve neutralization of charge.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The coagulation-flocculation process can be used as a preliminary or intermediary step between other water or wastewater treatment processes like filtration and sedimentation.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Iron and aluminium salts are the most widely used coagulants but salts of other metals such as titanium and zirconium have been found to be highly effective as well.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulation is affected only by the type of coagulant used, its dose and mass; pH and initial turbidity of the water that is being treated; and properties of the pollutants present.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The effectiveness of the coagulation process is also affected by pretreatments like oxidation.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] In a colloidal suspension, particles will settle very slowly or not at all because the colloidal particles carry surface electrical charges that mutually repel each other.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] This surface charge is most commonly evaluated in terms of zeta potential, the electrical potential at the slipping plane.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] To induce coagulation, a coagulant (typically a metallic salt) with the opposite charge is added to the water to overcome the repulsive charge and "destabilize" the suspension.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] For example, the colloidal particles are negatively charged and alum is added as a coagulant to create positively charged ions.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Once the repulsive charges have been neutralized (since opposite charges attract), van der Waals force will cause the particles to cling together (agglomerate) and form micro floc.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The dose of the coagulant to be used can be determined via the jar test.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The jar test involves exposing same volume samples of the water to be treated to different doses of the coagulant and then simultaneously mixing the samples at a constant rapid mixing time.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The microfloc formed after coagulation further undergoes flocculation and is allowed to settle.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Then the turbidity of the samples is measured and the dose with the lowest turbidity can be said to be optimum.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Despite its widespread use in the performance of so-called "dewatering experiments", the jar test is limited in its usefulness due to several disadvantages.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] For example, evaluating the performance of prospective coagulants or flocculants requires both significant volumes of water/wastewater samples (liters) and experimental time (hours).
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] This limits the scope of the experiments which can be conducted, including the addition of replicates.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Furthermore, the analysis of jar test experiments produces results which are often only semi-quantitative.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Coupled with the wide range of chemical coagulants and flocculants that exist, it has been remarked that determining the most appropriate dewatering agent as well as the optimal dose "is widely considered to be more of an ‘art’ rather than a ‘science’".
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] As such, dewatering performance tests such as the jar test lend themselves well to miniaturization.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] An automated device for determining the coagulant dose is the Streaming Current Detector (SCD).
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The SCD measures the net surface charge of the particles and shows a streaming current value of 0 when the charges are neutralized (cationic coagulants neutralize the anionic colloids).
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] At this value (0), the coagulant dose can be said to be optimum.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulation itself results in the formation of floc but flocculation is required to help the floc further aggregate and settle.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] The coagulation-flocculation process itself removes only about 60%-70% of Natural Organic Matter (NOM) and thus, other processes like oxidation, filtration and sedimentation are necessary for complete raw water or wastewater treatment.
[src:particle-aggregation/coagulation-water-treatment] Coagulant aids (polymers that bridge the colloids together) are also often used to increase the efficiency of the process.
[src:particle-aggregation/coalescence-chemistry] In chemistry, **coalescence** is a process in which two phase domains of the same composition come together and form a larger phase domain.
[src:particle-aggregation/coalescence-chemistry] In other words, the process by which two or more separate masses of miscible substances seem to "pull" each other together should they make the slightest contact.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Particle agglomeration can be a reversible or irreversible process.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Particle agglomerates defined as "hard agglomerates" are more difficult to redisperse to the initial single particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] In the course of agglomeration, the agglomerates will grow in size, and as a consequence they may settle to the bottom of the container, which is referred to as sedimentation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Alternatively, a colloidal gel may form in concentrated suspensions which changes its rheological properties.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The reverse process whereby particle agglomerates are re-dispersed as individual particles, referred to as peptization, hardly occurs spontaneously, but may occur under stirring or shear.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Colloidal particles may also remain dispersed in liquids for long periods of time (days to years).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] This phenomenon is referred to as *colloidal stability* and such a suspension is said to be functionally *stable*.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Stable suspensions are often obtained at low salt concentrations or by addition of chemicals referred to as *stabilizers* or *stabilizing agents*.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The stability of particles, colloidal or otherwise, is most commonly evaluated in terms of zeta potential.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] This parameter provides a readily quantifiable measure of interparticle repulsion, which is the key inhibitor of particle aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Similar agglomeration processes occur in other dispersed systems too.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] In emulsions, they may also be coupled to droplet coalescence, and not only lead to sedimentation but also to creaming.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] In aerosols, airborne particles may equally aggregate and form larger clusters (e.g., soot).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] A well dispersed colloidal suspension consists of individual, separated particles and is stabilized by repulsive inter-particle forces.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] When the repulsive forces weaken or become attractive through the addition of a coagulant, particles start to aggregate.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] In the early stage of the aggregation process, the suspension mainly contains individual particles.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The rate of this phenomenon is characterized by the aggregation rate coefficient k.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Since doublet formation is a second order rate process, the units of this coefficients are m3s−1 since particle concentrations are expressed as particle number per unit volume (m−3).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Since absolute aggregation rates are difficult to measure, one often refers to the dimensionless stability ratio W, defined as $W={\frac {k_{\text{fast}}}{k}}$ where *k*fast is the aggregation rate coefficient in the fast regime, and k the coefficient at the conditions of interest.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The stability ratio is close to unity in the fast regime, increases in the slow regime, and becomes very large when the suspension is stable.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Often, colloidal particles are suspended in water.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] In this case, they accumulate a surface charge and an electrical double layer forms around each particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The overlap between the diffuse layers of two approaching particles results in a repulsive double layer interaction potential, which leads to particle stabilization.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] When salt is added to the suspension, the electrical double layer repulsion is screened, and van der Waals attraction become dominant and induce fast aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The figure on the right shows the typical dependence of the stability ratio W versus the electrolyte concentration, whereby the regimes of slow and fast aggregation are indicated.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The table below summarizes the critical coagulation concentration (CCC) ranges for different net charge of the counter ion.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The charge is expressed in units of elementary charge.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] This dependence reflects the Schulze–Hardy rule, which states that the CCC varies as the inverse sixth power of the counter ion charge.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The CCC also depends on the type of ion somewhat, even if they carry the same charge.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] This dependence may reflect different particle properties or different ion affinities to the particle surface.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Since particles are frequently negatively charged, multivalent metal cations thus represent highly effective coagulants.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Quantitative interpretation of colloidal stability was first formulated within the DLVO theory.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] This theory confirms the existence slow and fast aggregation regimes, even though in the slow regime the dependence on the salt concentration is often predicted to be much stronger than observed experimentally.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The Schulze–Hardy rule can be derived from DLVO theory as well.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Other mechanisms of colloid stabilization are equally possible, particularly, involving polymers.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] When polymers chains adsorb to particles loosely, a polymer chain may bridge two particles, and induce bridging forces.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] This situation is referred to as bridging flocculation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] When particle aggregation is solely driven by diffusion, one refers to *perikinetic* aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Aggregation can be enhanced through shear stress (e.g., stirring).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The latter case is called *orthokinetic* aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] As the aggregation process continues, larger clusters form.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The growth occurs mainly through encounters between different clusters, and therefore one refers to cluster-cluster aggregation process.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The resulting clusters are irregular, but statistically self-similar.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] where *d* is the mass fractal dimension.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Depending whether the aggregation is fast or slow, one refers to diffusion limited cluster aggregation (DLCA) or reaction limited cluster aggregation (RLCA).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The clusters have different characteristics in each regime.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] DLCA clusters are loose and ramified (*d* ≈ 1.8), while the RLCA clusters are more compact (*d* ≈ 2.1).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The cluster size distribution is also different in these two regimes.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] DLCA clusters are relatively monodisperse, while the size distribution of RLCA clusters is very broad.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The larger the cluster size, the faster their settling velocity.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Therefore, aggregating particles sediment and this mechanism provides a way for separating them from suspension.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] At higher particle concentrations, the growing clusters may interlink, and form a particle gel.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Such a gel is an elastic solid body, but differs from ordinary solids by having a very low elastic modulus.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] When aggregation occurs in a suspension composed of similar monodisperse colloidal particles, the process is called *homoaggregation* (or *homocoagulation*).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] When aggregation occurs in a suspension composed of dissimilar colloidal particles, one refers to *heteroaggregation* (or *heterocoagulation*).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] The simplest heteroaggregation process occurs when two types of monodisperse colloidal particles are mixed.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] While the first two processes correspond to homoaggregation in pure suspensions containing particles A or B, the last reaction represents the actual heteroaggregation process.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Each of these reactions is characterized by the respective aggregation coefficients *k*AA, *k*BB, and *k*AB.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] For example, when particles A and B bear positive and negative charge, respectively, the homoaggregation rates may be slow, while the heteroaggregation rate is fast.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] In contrast to homoaggregation, the heteroaggregation rate accelerates with decreasing salt concentration.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Clusters formed at later stages of such heteroaggregation processes are even more ramified that those obtained during DLCA (*d* ≈ 1.4).
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] An important special case of a heteroaggregation process is the deposition of particles on a substrate.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Early stages of the process correspond to the attachment of individual particles to the substrate, which can be pictures as another, much larger particle.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Later stages may reflect blocking of the substrate through repulsive interactions between the particles, while attractive interactions may lead to multilayer growth, and is also referred to as ripening.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] These phenomena are relevant in membrane or filter fouling.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Numerous experimental techniques have been developed to study particle aggregation.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Most frequently used are time-resolved optical techniques that are based on transmittance or scattering of light.
[src:particle-aggregation/particle-aggregation] Particle aggregation is a widespread phenomenon, which spontaneously occurs in nature but is also widely explored in manufacturing.
